  <div class="container" style="padding-top: var(--space-xl);">
    <AnalystNotes
      title="Understanding Broker Types and Fee Structures"
      icon="üí∞"
      id="fee-structures-notes"
      variant="light"
    >
      <h4>Not All Brokers Are Created Equal</h4>
      <p>Understanding broker business models helps you make informed choices. The "best" broker depends entirely on how you trade.</p>

      <h5>Market Makers vs ECN/STP Brokers</h5>
      <p><strong>Market Makers</strong> take the other side of your trade internally. They profit from spreads and sometimes from your losses. This creates a potential conflict of interest, but also provides guaranteed fills and fixed spreads - valuable for beginners who want predictable costs.</p>

      <p><strong>ECN/STP Brokers</strong> route your orders directly to liquidity providers (banks, hedge funds). They make money purely from commissions. You get raw interbank spreads (sometimes 0.0 pips), but pay commission per lot. Better for scalpers and high-volume traders where tight spreads matter more than commission costs.</p>

      <h5>Spread-Only vs Commission-Based Pricing</h5>
      <p><strong>Spread-only accounts</strong> embed all costs in the spread. If EUR/USD shows 1.2 pips, that's your total cost. Simple and transparent - you always know what you're paying. Better for beginners and swing traders making fewer large trades.</p>

      <p><strong>Commission-based accounts</strong> show raw spreads (often 0.0-0.2 pips) plus charge $3-7 commission per lot traded. Total cost is spread + commission. Often cheaper for active traders, but requires math to compare true costs. Preferred by scalpers and day traders.</p>

      <h5>Which Is Best For You?</h5>
      <p>If you're making 1-5 trades per week with larger position sizes, spread-only accounts are simpler and often cheaper. If you're scalping 20+ trades per day with tight stops, commission-based raw spread accounts will save you thousands annually. Our AI matcher considers your trading frequency when making recommendations.</p>
